      passage: `<p>Microplastics are tiny fragments of plastic waste that collect throughout the ocean. Stretches of ocean that hold heavier concentrations of microplastic particles also tend to have smaller and fewer waves. In a recent study, Naomi Vinstra and colleagues showed that microplastic concentration on its own cannot explain this dampened wave activity: the concentration that would be needed to cause the observed effect is far higher than what these waters actually hold. Instead, the researchers found, surfactants&mdash;chemicals often used in the making of plastics&mdash;leach out of microplastics into the surrounding water, where their wave-flattening effect is far stronger.</p>`,
